text:
I usually go to this drive-thru less PanEx just because of it's proximity to my house and usually as a lunch quickie/post grocery shopping exhaustion nom.

I have never had service issues here, usually the gals behind the counter are quick and courteous and I am in and out in literally under 5mins. I almost prefer that it doesn't have a drive-thru because I have never had an incorrect order here, even when I use the app to pre-order my food for pickup.

Though, on my most recent visit, I went right before closing and was not even greeted. I stood there waiting for them to take my order, but the staff were too busy joking around w/each other to acknowledge my existence. I also saw the scraggly remains of the chow mein and the heat-lamp stale orange chicken and decided to save myself from General Tso's revenge to try my luck another day. I am hoping the sub-par service was a one-off and not a trend.

So word to the wise...never go 20mins or less before close and expect fresh or even quasi-edible food.

text:
Hate to do this, but what a disappointment. Hard pass on this Panda Express location. We definitely won't be back. And this is from people who normally love Panda Express. We frequent other Panda Express locations quite a bit. In fact, Panda Express is one of my kids' favorite meals when we grab fast food -- so we know our dishes and what they and the portions should be. This one isn't a drive thru location but we had errands in that part of town and hadn't yet eaten. Fine, so let's go down. That being said, you would have thought the customer service would have been better given the person to person interaction. Wrong.

We normally get a Kid's meal for my Little, half beef broccoli half orange chicken, with split fried rice and chow mein. The lady behind the counter said we couldn't do half and half. What? Okay fine, we don't like to make waves. So I ended up getting an adult meal for my small in size seven year old so she could get the meats she wanted -- she doesn't even finish the kid meal so what a waste. I watched the lady pour the kids meal into an adult container and resignedly put in our two half meat choices.

We ordered a total of three adult meals to go -- and you could literally right before your eyes see how stingy the lady was being on portions. Not two scoops of rice, but one and a half. It was almost like watching her perform a mental calculation of how little can I put it in here and still make it passable (barely). She was actually pouring food out of the scooper so she wouldn't put too "much." My thought was, wow. But what are you going to say? Put more food in the container, please?

Sure enough, come home with our three adult meals and there's very little food. Now, it's Panda Express and cheap so I don't expect five courses or a buffet or overflowing plates. But this was meager. And tight. And unpleasant all around. Very lacking in what we are used to from other locations. As much as I normally like Panda Express, I felt ripped off with this experience. And really, how hard is it to give half and half on the meats? Not like we'd be getting more food -- clearly.

Food quality was about the same as other locations. The service -- just plain bad.

text:
So we're both rushing to get to the movie theatre after work, and there's no time to eat at home, so we come here, because the Panda is delicious. My girlfriend gets the Plate, and I get the Bigger Plate. 

Her chow mein was very good with a good mix of veggies in it to bring some freshness to the heavy noodles. The Orange Chicken is super classic to this place, it's delicious, but it's also very strong in flavor. I recommend sampling it before you order it, just in case. The Honey Sesame Chicken Breast was even better, though. The honey and the sesame flavor were present, but more subdued. I could have eaten a gallon of this stuff. 

I got the fried rice, it was exactly what you're picturing. I also got the orange chicken. I got the Grilled Teriyaki Chicken (adding the optional sauce on top), and wow it was delicious. It didn't taste like fried chicken tossed in sauce. It tasted grilled and tender. Solid. But the best thing I had this visit was the Beijing Beef. The grilled beef had a solid crust on the outside of each strip and it was tender and delicious. The peppers and onions it was mixed in with paired perfectly with it. 

The food was as expected, superb. I really enjoyed the service on this particular visit. I asked the gentleman at the counter what he recommended in terms of the entrees, and he started throwing free sample after free sample at me and my girlfriend. He was so nice, and I got to pinpoint exactly what I wanted. 

Overall, this was good. I used to think this place was overpriced, but now that inflation has made everything else in the world more expensive, these prices weren't so bad. We certainly got a lot of bang for our buck. Come here. I approve.

text:

I will say the customer service in here is great, everyone is nice, friendly, attentive, ect. The manager himself has always been friendly and is always on the floor working just as hard as the staff it seems. Store is always clean, never super buy when I've gone.

I'll give it four stars because the food isn't my favorite in the world, but the customer service is top notch each time I come in.

text:
First the pros: Fast, clean & inviting. 
Unfortunately, the pros are not enough to convince me the food is worth writing home about. 
Gripes abound. "Grrr". 
For starters I was very amused (in an unpleasant way) to see the cooks weighing and measuring everything about to be dumped in a large vat, er wok, of hot oil (which appears to be the only cooking method available). While I am not against a business making money, I am against large chains reminding me that I am about to plunk down my hard earned money during hard times so that the corporate big wigs can still earn their more than comfortable salaries. 
OK, so no big deal - as long as my food is good. I do not mind paying my fair share of dough for some good eating - but for this crap I have a problem with. For starters, I estimate that about 75% of the weigh of my food is starch (rice, chow mein). And if that wasn't bad enough, the little bit of protein served is dry! And not just the protein, but rather all the amenities therein too! I suspect this is due to the fact that this establishment still shells out food a la McDonald's of yesteryear, meaning they prepare their food in bulk and store it in a metal hotel pan over a hot water bath until a customer is ready to be served. That's cool and all if it's constantly busy, but it's not cool during down times when there is only a few customers (which is the time I was in). 

To make a long story short, I could have had a better tasting fresher meal (and cheaper) out of the Fred Meyer freezer across the parking lot.
name: Panda Express

text: Zero. Zero. Zero. Zero. Zero. Zero.  This place should just be a big fat ol Zero.  I've been here more than a few times though mall food isn't really my deal. text: I am stating my rating experience as a DoorDash driver who came in on a recent Monday night around 7:30 to pick up a customer order. Came in and did not receive the usual "welcome to Panda Express" verbal greeting so that's not a good sign. I got to the online order pickup spot and there were two staff members counting out moneys at the register and did not acknowledge my presence for almost 15 seconds. After some time one of them finally asked me for the customer's name for the order which I gave out. She proceeded to pack up the order and then right before tying up the bag, surprisingly she threw in utensils and napkins in not a very gentle manner. I then kindly asked if she has soy sauce and chili sauce packets to put in. She said they do not carry the latter..? I looked at her wildly and said fine but in my mind and experience, how could you not supply chili or sriracha sauces like all the other Panda Expresses I've been to?! BTW I have over 2000 deliveries under my belt so clearly I think I have some knowledge of proper restaurant operation and efficiency. I wish I had gotten the name of the staff member I encountered at that Panda Express but I just wanted to leave with my customer order without any further drama. Will not return to that place given how poorly the service runs.

text:
This location is good. I've never had any real problems. It's unfortunate that our favorite items keep getting discontinued. I'll miss you, sesame chicken.

I have 3 rules for eating at Panda Express:

1. Never order site unseen. The quality is never consistent. There's a chance that the food you get may have been sitting around, and is now dried up. Get a sample of anything you're considering.

2. Never go near closing time. The food is almost certain to have dried up, as they are not trying to make anything fresh close to closing. While that makes sense, I'm usually diappointed.

3. SAVE YOUR RECEIPT. Do the survey, and get a free entree with your next meal purchase. Not a bad deal!

text:
I was hungry for something like Moo Goo Gai Pan and in a hurry. I thought I'd give Panda Express a try. I pull up to the drive through, take a look at the pretty pictures and decide on Broccoli Beef. It was one of a few mostly green pictures. I had high hopes. After paying I get a bag with a tiny little box in it. I drive away hoping it's one of those magic Chinese takeout boxes. You know the kind that you are amazed at how much food they can pack in there? Either that, or I got a kids meal by mistake. Abracadabra, open the box and shoot - no magic here. 7 pieces of broccoli and four small slivers of beef. The only magic act was that $3.50 disappeared from my wallet.

Now I know why they were asking if I wanted the two entrée or three entree "deal". It would take at least two to provide a decent amount for lunch. I have to add that even though there was not much volume the flavor was actually better than expected. The service window person was pleasant also.

text:
This Panda Express is located just down from many authentic Asian restaurants. I chose this Panda Express because I was headed to a 3 hour meeting (with one scheduled break) and wanted (1) quick, (2) something I knew I would like, (3) something I knew my stomach would tolerate without issue. 

I love authentic Asian food and am usually quite adventurous, but sometimes, one just needs an Americanized version of Asian food - not too spicy. Panda Express generally delivers reasonably uniform quality regardless of the location. I was not disappointed. The honey-chicken and Beijing beef were the typical fair, although less spicy than I have eaten in other Panda Expresses. Given the meeting, no complaints about the less spice.

The staff was very nice and offered tastes of items. My representative was a good sales person as he offered me several upgrades at minor charges from appetizers to an extra meat. As I am a sales and marketing professional, this salesmanship simply made me smile. He was not pushy about the offers either - just informative and enthusiastic.

The front parking lot is narrow. Please be mindful as you back your car out not to clobber the cars in the next row.

text:
Is this a high-fallutin' Austin eatery?  You'd be kidding yourself if you said yes.  However, Panda Express fills a few niches which is why it gets four stars:

--Low-cal and 'healthier' choices for those who just can't do 'burger-style' fast food very often for health/other reasons (that's me!)
--Quick service with a smile
--Vegetables, and plenty of them, not overcooked
--samples.

At this restaurant, both my husband (who likes a good Orange Chicken once in a while) and me can enjoy a good meal.  I like the outright nutrition information posted on their website and in store that tell me what each item has in cholesterol, sodium content, etc. so I can make informed choices while eating out. 

Thanks for helping making eating "fast" food a little bit easier, Panda Express!

text:
It was around 2:00 p.m. when I arrived for lunch and saw a wild Iron Chef type guy stirring items in a frenzy using a giant wok.  Otherwise, there were warming trays of Chinese food offerings. I felt like I was straddling two different realities.  Is it fresh or is the wok guy a shill?

It is Asian American.  Not as spicy as I like nor as Asian as I like but it will do since they have the packets of hot mustard and I'm already here. The Cashew Chicken was free (thanks to a coupon) and for a little over $3.00 I added an egg roll (meh) and fried rice (another meh) and a water. 

I accidentally (without thinking) put green tea in my cup when I really wanted water. Don't make this mistake.  The water is much better.  

Sometimes I do fall for the "free" deals and disappoint myself and my taste buds.  But this did not register as high on the disappointment scale as the economy, a spilled bottle of Malbec, or my neighbors pet sitting a screeching Cockatoo for a month.

text:
Heck, I admit I like cheap Chinese food.  It's right there for the world to see in my Yelp profile.

However, today was definitely a meh experience.  It started with a long line that moved slowly, although that's not Panda's fault.   However, a lack of trays for those of us eating in makes for an awkward serving line.  Couple that with them being out of the chicken eggrolls.  The lady on the serving line tried talking me out of the eggroll several times, first telling me of a six minute wait, then offering me the cream cheese puffs or the vegetable egg roll instead, then seeming almost disappointed when I insisted on the chicken egg roll.

So, the food.  Well, the orange chicken and rice were the exact cheap Chinese food that I sometimes crave.  But the eggroll that I waited so long for?   It was hot on the outside but the vegetables inside tasted barely cooked at all.   So, for $10 and change, I had serviceable chicken and rice and a Pepsi product (Panda doesn't have unsweetened tea.).

I think I'm gonna have to find a different purveyor of cheap Chinese to satisfy my craving.

text:
My dad LOVES this place.  Apparently, everytime he would head over to my side of town, he would surreptitiously eat here before visiting me.  One day he finally offered to take me there.

To be honest, I wasn't impressed.  I believe that they'll cook you a fresh dish if you ask, but I didn't.  So, instead I just chose from whatever meager, dried-out portions remained in the chafing dishes. 

The taste was about what you'd expect from a Chinese buffet.  But the food was lukewarm at best.  Luckily I have a strong stomach as eating chicken that's been sitting around for awhile could've been bad.  My dad, of course, was eating happily away.  Being the polite daughter that I am, I pretended to enjoy it.  Who am I to criticize a free meal?   

In retrospect, I think it had to do with the entrees I chose.  I like mixed meat and vegetable dishes, not the typical americanized fare.  You know, General Tso's or anything else that consists of huge chunks of deep-fried meat.  But since that stuff seems to be more popular it's understandable that the cooks would continuously be setting out fresh, hot portions.  

Last word of advice: If they still have it, DON'T try the Sobe Cranberry-Grapefruit drink from the soda fountain.  I like cranberry, I like grapefruit - should've been good, right?  Wrong.  It tasted exactly like cherry Robitussin.

text:
Panda Express is Panda Express - one comes here for a quick meal with something resembling veggies and not for authentic Chinese food.

The two star rating is entirely for the drive-through service and not for anything else.

1) First time I went there, my husbands two-entrée meal was incorrect. Ok, fine, maybe I was unclear on the speaker as the ticket reflected what they'd given us.

2) Second time I went there, both my meal and my husband's meals were incorrect. They were correct on the ticket. I filled out a corporate feedback form, and they sent us a pair of free meals. That does make me feel better.

3) Third time I go there with free meals. Aaaaand, they mess up my husbands order. It was correct on the ticket and, once again, boxed up incorrectly. This time I had the sense to check the order before driving off, so the error was corrected.

Conclusion: stay away from the drive-through. If I got to this Panda again I will remove my person from the car so I can oversee them as they package my order.

text: Wow, the family and I have been coming  to this location for years, its the kids favorite....but, when they don't even finish their dinners, and say its tastes different and not very good there is a problem! Lets begin, service as always was great, friendly faces greeting me. Of course they offered samples...the battered walnut shrimp, it wasn't clear if there was a tail on it or not...it was covered in batter...yeah it still had its tail. I'd had the orange chicken before, but sure I'll take a sample. Gristly and tasteless. I should have seen the signs...I brought the food home to my kids, like I've done several times before. The rice looked great, but was so bland...like flavorless. Disappointing. And the orange chicken...what I'm sure is the #1 seller...also didn't have much flavor orange or otherwise, but it gets worse...it was really chewy...like it had come from a bad part of the chicken. Like poor quality chicken. Maybe it was just a bad batch, the meat, maybe not Panda's fault...unless they've started using lower quality of meat...to save money...speaking of money...did they start using smaller styrofoam containers? Seems like there was less orange chicken as well as blackened chicken...which seemed lighter than usual in terms of meat, with a lot more celery and onion. Smaller portions were probably the best considering, how crummy the food was. Like already said the kids didn't even finish what they had. We may or may not go back. Are they trying to cut corners? Don't care? Careless? Is this only location with these issues...a one time Panda experience or...something that's been coming?

text: I had a craving for orange chicken so stopped in for lunch.  12:15pm on a Monday.  There were two people working.  The customer ahead of me ordered an item to which the girl responded that they don't have a cook to cook it.  Curious , I asked if you don't have a cook how was the rest of the food made?  She answered that there was one there but he left and they aren't sure where he is now.  I waited 5minutes while the one girl assisted the people ahead of me.  The other girl was on the phone asking how to cook something.  Finally the girl finishes assisting the people ahead of me taking their card and running it at the register.  Without washing her hands or putting gloves on comes to assist me with gathering my food.  I ask her if she is going to wash her hands or put gloves on.    She rolls her eyes and steps out of site for maybe 30seconds and comes back.  It didn't seem like a reasonable time to sanitize before handling food so I left.  Huge waste of time!  I feel bad that the two girls were left on there own.  However, don't appreciate someone in the food industry not following hand washing guidelines. text: We arrived just before closing. Manny, Mark, Kierstynn and Yessica were beginning to clean up, but not in the sense where we felt we were a disruption to them closing. They were all very happy doing their jobs. We were greeted with smiles and thanksgiving. The food was still very fresh and super hot. Our portions were large, and the price was reasonable. Yessica told us to enjoy ourselves, even though they were considered closed 10 minutes after our arrival. None of the employees made a fuss or cleaned around us making us feel like we had to rush and eat. They all stayed in the kitchen and stayed busy there. My ONLY complaint is that at closing we were told the remaining food would be tossed...I asked to buy everything for a respectable price, but I was told I needed to pay the $9 or so for the "to go" containers. I would have liked to have been given a deal for the end of the day leftovers...Just sayin' - This gal could have walked out on cloud nine...instead of cloud 8! Bless you all! text:
TRUST ME.  I'm Asian.  I know Awesome Asian (like myself, Jackie Chan & Panda Express), I know un-awesome Asian (like PSY's Gangnam Style).

I rate according the category - Panda is clearly a fast food place so amongst quick food this is for sure a 5-star.  I'm surprised b/c you see, I'm Asian and I'd make fun of my friends who go here b/c I'd always think it's not real Chinese food.  When I think authentic Chinese I'm always drawn to dim-sum or a foodie-foo foo place that is $$.  

BUT, I am brilliantly surprised by my new liking of $ Chinese!  This is NOT like the greasy all-fried places that I dislike, similar to chicken's feet.  This is modern and fresh...and (mostly) healthy.  I love that I can get a 2-entree dish for under 7 buck-a-roos...and they cook up fresh veggies if you don't want the noodle or rice carb.  I LOVE the perfectly steamed broccoli and green beans that have just a bit of crunch to them! 

The modern decor and counter ordering is nice and easy.  And to see all the fresh cut veggies in plastic bins in the fridge window is awesome...they don't use those horrible frozen square carrots and peas here!

Not that they were out or I would have to wait, just a "Nah."  So I ordered the teriyaki chicken instead.  They told me it would be out in 10 minutes.  A bit much for a fast food joint, but whatever.  25 minutes later, I asked where my chicken was.  Apparently, the cook forgot to make it at all.  I finally just said, "I want my money back."  The clerk told me that I would have to wait for the manager to come back to work.  10 minutes later, the "manager" just walked in and refunded my money, but didn't bother asking what happened or even apologize for the inconvenience.  Oh, and she refused to give me my receipt back so I could fill out the customer experience survey.  What a crap hole.  There are about 100 other Chinese food places within a 5 minute drive of this place.  Go to literally any of them before subjecting yourself to this awful place.

text:
My family used to get the Panda Feast and many extra sides almost every Friday for our movie night. I L-O-V-E-D the atmosphere and amazingly friendly employees, they knew our order when I walked in and after making eye contact would tell the cooks to start fresh Rangoons and Spring Rolls ( we have a 20 min drive home ). Our containers were ALWAYS filled and packed down and filled more. Absolutely above and beyond. 


  That said it appears after a few employees have left and new people have been hired on everything has changed, most of all their customer service. I understand a few mistakes,

 I understand being new, I understand being overwhelmed at the lines they deal with on Friday/Saturday nights.  

I cannot understand or look past the last 3 -4 times ( yes we kept our hopes high ) 
the level of filth, the rude people behind the counter, messing up my order multiple times ( after supposedly checking it before they knot the bag shut ) and then basically calling us liars for bringing it up. The COLD chicken ( and not because of our drive, we usually still have to be careful of burns when we open our taped up boxes at home)  and super dry to the point I hurt my tooth Lo Mein noodles!! Then all of a sudden the price for the exact thing we have ordered for almost a year starts to vary every time we go. I literally looked at my bank statements and can see the 2-4 dollar variance per visit. Huh. 

It's too bad because my family enjoyed our movie nights and the kids still ask for this food, we just don't have any other PE within driving distance that I want to waste money trying.  We miss the previous staff of 3-4 months back. 

 Oh and they stop making food well before close, expect an attitude and very little choices if you come anywhere near closing, Mostly the stuff nobody ever orders that sits out. No noodles etc.

text:
"Oh bliss. Mall food."

That above quote was from an old episode of "Buffy" in which she eats Americanized Chinese food at a mall. I would assume it is Panda Express. Anyways, Panda Express is your typical mall food, served really fast and the food is right in front of your face. The lines in here are usually long. I have only visited three Panda Expresses, one at the Waterford Lakes Shopping Center in Orlando, FL, the one in Universal Citywalk Orlando, and then the branch at the Riviera food court in Las Vegas. 

The Waterford location is at a mall near UCF and lines are usually long during lunch.  I usually get the orange chicken and broccoli beef with the half and half rice and lo mein, and sometimes the eggrolls.   The food is mall food, but it is considerably better than the other choices. Usually one meal is both my lunch and dinner, since they give you huge portions. On most of my visits the food is newly cooked and the chicken is crunchy. However there are times in which the chicken is kind of old. 

When you think Vegas, you usually think buffet, but I was really hungry and decided to try the Panda Express at the Riviera. The line was longer than a theme park ride (no exaggerating!) and the good thing about it is the food is constantly fresh and newly cooked. I ordered the same items and I was not disappointed. However for some odd reason I felt hungry after that and ate at the Slots O' Fun restaurant (where they have 75 cent footlongs) and was so full of food, I can barely move! 

The CityWalk branch is open really late.  It's a joint that drunks like to stop by and pig out like after several hurricanes and other liquors nothing beats Americanized Chinese.

Overall, Panda Express is a decent restaurant. And yes, it is mall food.

text:
I've been to Panda several times at several locations and I've honestly never been so disappointed until I came to this location. 

This location is very understaffed. Upon walking in, we were welcomed to a long line that reached to the front door. We got in line around 8:25PM and did not reach the front of the line until 8:50PM. I do not blame the workers at all for being slow. This place really needs more people. I almost feel bad for the workers because they are on their feet constantly. The line didn't die down while we were there. 

As far as food goes, there isn't much to say about Americanized Chinese food. The food is average, but isn't as fresh as I would like, which all leads to back to the location being poorly staffed... 

In addition, the cashier who rang me up forgot to give me a receipt. They clearly have a sign that says if they forget to give you your receipt, the meal is free. I realized I didn't get a receipt a few seconds after sitting down. When I went back to the cashier, I mentioned he didn't give me a receipt, and simply gave me the receipt he intended to give me. I looked at him and said that the sign said the meal is on them... he looked at me confused and said "what?" I pointed at the sign on the register and he turned it around, read it, paused for a few seconds... and said "oh we can take care of that!" He was very friendly and I appreciated his customer service. 

All in all, management needs to be revisited and reassessed here. Service is poor and should have better training to inform their employees about their policies. I do plan to continue coming here when I get occasional cravings, but I hope to see improvements in staffing when I return.

text:
So we don't go here as often as the past. This americanized Chinese spot has a cafeteria style line selection or you can order off a menu but I've never seen something do that. 

At least when ordering thru the line you first choose between brown or white steam rice or fried rice or chow mein noodles or steamed veggies.  That's the largest portion of the meal. I tend to order half steamed veggies and half of which ever of the others strikes me.

Next there are about a dozen different preparations of chicken or beef and occasionally there will be one or two shimp choices. Some are listed as spicy  but are minimally so. There are usually a couple with dried Chinese chilies .

Today those were even mild.

Typically food is fast. Today however there was no one in the kitchen when we first got there. I tried ordering the crispy shrimp and was told they cooked it to order.... first time in 10 or more years I heard of that.
Got the rest of our food, paid for it,all inclusive of the shrimp and finally asked when I would get it.

They had forgotten the order. So they immediately cooked it and also paid me back it's cost!

Good job!

The food is okay. My vegetarian son says they are not veggian friendly.  But the food comes quickly, they have nice seating inside and out and accommodate my requests usually.

text:
My family and I stopped by at 8pm for a late dinner. As we approached the doors we saw a customer exit her minivan as she waited just past the exit of the drive thru, yelling at the employee delivering another order to a car. The customer was complaining how she was told it'd be at least 5 minutes just for some sauce. That should have been my first clue at what our experience was going to be.

I joked with my family that if what they wanted wasn't in the bowl then choose something else. After all, we all know this location is famous for being out of everything. Sure enough, this trip didn't disappoint. Of the entire selection they were out of TEN items; empty bowls with no display of hustle refill them. Even the orange chicken only had enough for two portions. One lonely egg roll sat alone in the bowl looking dry as a brick. Even more confusing was the single spring roll. How can you have one single spring roll when they're sold two to an order?

We ordered what we could, substituting what we wanted with what was available. The employee accidentally dropped his Huntington pen into the bowl of teriyaki chicken and then pulled it out with his bare hands as if it wasn't a big deal and placed it in his pocket. I can only imagine what kind of cooties lived on that pen as it's the same one customers use to sign when they use their charges/debit card, let alone what else the guy had in his pocket.

To wrap things up we were asked if we wanted fortune cookies. I guess these are now considered extras instead of being part of the meal. As we ate we continued to watch order after order for the drive thru being delivered to cars waiting in the parking lot.

We'll definitely consider other dining options the next time we're in the area.
name: Panda Express

text:
Had a bad experience Saturday nite at the Panda. Went in with high expectations. First up - the music being played was so loud, the servers seemed unable to actually hear customer orders. I ordered my standard "1/2 noodles, 1/2 veggies". The server created a plate of 1/2 noodles, 1/2 fried rice. I said, that's not what I ordered. So he asked again what it was that I wanted. I again said "1/2 noodles, 1/2 veggies". What I got back was 1/2 noodles, 1/2 white rice. The line behind me was growing, so I gave up and went on to the next server to order. I ordered several things that were okay, and then I ordered Beijing Beef. The server said "Oh, this will be very spicy." I said "You all can't make it spicy enough for me.". We went to check out. No offer of chopsticks. No offer of fortune cookie. we sat down and I began to eat. was still frustrated by the lack of veggies on my plate. Then I tasted the Beijing beef. Terribly oversauced with the sweet sauce. No evidence of spiciness. 
I am torn about whether or not to go back, at least to this location, when I so frequently find the spice level too little. The confusion over a customer who wants vegetables being given rice just seems inexcusable.

text:

text:
I get it, kid. You needed a job and you got one at Panda Express. It's not your career. It's not your dream job. But seriously there's no need for sarcasm and attitude.

I usually like Panda Express.  I went to this location for the very first time Thursday night and was met by the Kid. You know the type.  Thoroughly unhappy that he's working there. Wished he had his phone in hand to check his texts or emails.

I ordered a 3-entree meal - in particular, Panda Express' current special - spare ribs. The Kid told me - and I quote - "We have to make those special. It'll take 15 minutes. Next time, why don't you try ordering online?"

Well, I was starving, so I told him I didn't mind waiting 15 minutes.  I looked at their selection and noticed that almost every entree pan was empty.  I asked the Kid, "Do you have any vegetables?"

No response. He's looking away, looking irritated.

"Excuse me?" I repeat. "Any vegetables?"

Finally he looks at me and says, "Do you see any?"

"No, that's why I asked you if you have any."

I get this huff, this sound as if I've asked him to make something from scratch.

"Whatever we have here," he replies.

When I checked out, the young lady there gave me a free drink because I had to wait for the ribs.  My other 2 entrees (shrimp with walnut, mushroom chicken) were fine, but the white rice was crunchy from being dry and overcooked.

15 minutes later, she brought over a plate of ribs - cold. Where they came from, I don't know. Why were they cold? Who knows.

text:
Panda Express has reopened after recovering from a bad case of short bus soccer mom driving Suburban from passenger seat. It was raining,  and this Circle C genius thought it prudent to edge the 'burb a few feet closer so the person she sent in for to go wouldn't get a couple more raindrops.  Well,  she succeeded in putting the 'burb through the plate glass window and inside the week-old restaurant, which then was shuttered with Plywood for a few weeks.

I'd been so anxious and hopeful that this place would have reasonable Asian food because it's so much closer to my house.  Understand that I saved my PE virginity for this store, so they held it in their hands to impress or depress.

The layout::
After figuring out that this was basically a reverse buffet (or Asian Luby's) I ordered fried rice, orange chicken, and kung pao chicken with a side of cheese rangoons and a small fountain drink.  Total damage was $9.31 with TT&L.  I thought that a bit expensive relative to regular buffets where the amount of food is not predetermined and you're not locked into just the two entrees you picked.

The food:
Food is served on undersized paper plates that are then filled heaping high so you think you're getting a lot of food.  What you get mostly is the side order, in my case, fried rice.  The entree portions are reasonable, and some couples might find that a two-portion entree can be shared, which would make for a cheap meal.

The taste of the food left a lot to be desired.  The best of the lot was the orange chicken, but it should be as this is one of their signature entrees.  I was impressed by the quality of the chicken in both dishes; I didn't taste any dark meat, stringy meat, or bones.

The kung pao chicken was well prepared, and I was very impressed with the vegetables that were included.  However, the flavor was rather blase.  

The fried rice I also found to be fairly flavorless.  I was longing for a packet or two of soy sauce to improve the flavor and raise my blood pressure.

The rangoons were OK, but just OK, and I wouldn't add them again.

The service.
There is no service after the cash register.  I even had to beg for napkins; I was issued three.  The tables are barren of even so much as a salt shaker. Chinese gets messy with all the sauces, and it took exactly three napkins to make it through the meal.  The staff is typical fast food; they could seemingly care less about your experience.

The atmosphere:
There are tables and trash cans and you.  You're expected to pick up after yourself when you leave.  It was quiet because there are few customers at the time I went there (around 5 PM on a Saturday).

Other Notes:
One thing I did note about Panda Express that is an issue for many is that they use no MSG in the preparation of their dishes.  Perhaps that's why the flavor was lacking and why I don't feel hyped or dropped after eating there.  I feel normal.

Summary:
All through the meal, I felt like I was cheating on my favorite Asian, Firebowl Cafe.  The food was almost as expensive and it wasn't nearly as good.  It didn't seem as artery clogging, but it wasn't what I had in mind, either.  The place wasn't as crowded and I didn't feel like I was about to rub elbows with the entire restaurant as I was eating.  But there was no friendliness, no welcoming, and no enthusiasm.  You'd think there would be more of that since this store was resurrected, but nope.

Two stars.  I left full, but not satisfied.  I see no point in going back with Firebowl so close and so much better.  The only way they could even tempt me is by adding a drive through, and that's already been tried once with disastrous results.

text:
Upon telling my boyfriend that I've never had panda express before... I think his jaw literally hit the floor, and we immediately left the house in the middle of the night to fix this sacrilege and get our snack on.

Food:

I can see why his jaw hit the floor. I never thought i would say that the best chiinese food I've ever had came out of a chain drive thru.... but here I am. Their cream cheese rangoons are TO DIE FOR.  They even rival the crab and cream cheese rangoons I used to get as a child from a little shop in my home town (which i still rave about to this day). The food came out promptly, and was hot and delicious.... they are very generous with the rice... no way anyone could finish that. So if you're thinking about getting 2 sides of rice.... 1 will probably do just fine.

Service:

This is the only place where I had to take away some stars. As someone who works in the service industry myself I am very patient and understanding when it comes to being waited on or going to any form of restaurant... but refusing to make someone something their order just because "closing time is around the corner" is far fetched..... management needs to provide their front of house staff with a little more training........ not a very "personable" group.

text:
Love the food here usually but today service was wacky and food was lacking. THREE people were talking on the speaker it was so difficult to be able to discern what was happening.
 I am very patient as a former restauranteur and gave them grace as it was clear some rocky form of training was in process. 
The chatter continued throughout the drive up time even when we got our boxes which for the first time ever the food was luke warm and missing items.
It tends to be one of the pricey choices for fast food so there is an expectation of fresher ingredients and at least served hot.
I always give locations multiple chances but sadly most people do not. I hope management reads these reviews. There is help needed at this location. 
No one else offers drive up food of this kind, they have a good niche. Here's hoping they get this sorted out before my next visit. ( note: this visit was before Covid 19 happened)

text: When I arrived at this restaurant Saturday there were 3 customers. I did not see any cars in the drive through. One man was an Uber driver waiting for an Uber Order, one man sitting at a table eating and one man waiting for his order. I went to the desk, told the female there that I wanted the Family Feast to go, she said OK and "Just a minute" and walked away. After a few minutes she walked back, grabbed some boxes and proceeded to write on them what I was ordering..I wanted the Walnut Shrimp she said it was still cooking but would be ready  in two to three minutes. Everything else I was ordering was available on the steam table. I paid for everything and she said to have a seat and as soon as it was ready she would bring it to me. While waiting close to 5 more customers came in..as soon as they placed their orders their food was dished up they paid sat and ate. Some of them even ordered the Walnut Shrimp. Then more and more customers came in, close to 15 more. Boxes of food were lined up along the heated area, employees kept picking them up and looking in them, I saw one employee stick his fingers into the container and move things around. People were getting impatient waiting for food. After 20 minutes I still had not received my order. When I asked an employee and showed her my receipt I was told "Things are still cooking" I told them to cancel my order and refund my money. After 5 minutes or so of discussion with the manager and the person who took my original order I was refunded. I was offered the food "for free" but really?? Why would I want food that had been sitting in boxes for about half an hour that had been repeatedly opened, looked at, touched ...I have eaten and ordered take out here before and NEVER experienced this ..not sure if I will ever go back...VERY VERY DISAPPOINTED The Uber driver got his order right before my confrontation with the manager and the other man was still waiting when I left because his order was wrong.

text:
Bollocks! Panda Express advertising is both a sham and a scam! Supposedly as part of the Asian new year celebration, this chain would give all customers (no purchase required plainly stated on all ads), a coupon for a small firecracker shrimp entree. 

We went to this place about an hour after they opened and lo and behold, 1 employee had no idea what this promo was about. A second employee said they had run out of the coupon/red pocket envelope. We were incredulous since they had run out of the coupon after only one hour of being open?!

Bad food and bad service can be forgiven due to someone having a bad day. Lies and deception should never be forgiven, especially for a business.

text:
I came here for a quick dinner before my flight left. I've had a good experience before at this location while in between flights so I decided to give it another try. The Line wasn't long but there was a lengthy wait for more Orange chicken. And the person ahead of me got the last scoops. I can't complain because I did receive fresh hot chicken. That is always a plus in my book. 

It's your standard panda express; I will say they are generous in the scoops of chicken they give you which is one reason I come back to this location when I'm in the airport. They are consistent with the quality of food. You know what to expect when you order panda express. Its not going to be PF chains quality but it's better than just stopping at McDonald's. The staff is very friendly and helpful. I ordered the combo with two entrées but they only gave me one entrée. I reported this to the cashier and she she was very quick with correcting the problem. Next time I'm flying through MCO and have a taste for Chinese ill be sure to stop by panda express.

text:
There comes a time in everyone's life when they have to get food from an airport. That choice comes with the fact that you know you are going to be ordering from largely chains with reduced menus and inflated prices. Not wanting to suffer from the horrible mark up that happens after going through security, we decided to hit up the food court at Orlando International Airport. It had been awhile since we have had Chinese (yes, yes, "American Chinese" in this case) so Panda Express seemed like a decent option.

All in all, the food was okay and about what we expected. We got the two entree rice plate with chicken and mushrooms and the black pepper chicken. Both were pretty greasy, but not disgustingly so. Of the two, the chicken and mushroom was the better one. The rice was standard, but fresh enough that the rice loving male component of this review team was happy. The portions were also nice, as we split the dish between us.

Overall, the place is comparable to other Panda Express outlets, so not a bad option for fans of the franchise.

text:
Orlando airport's large food court is full of chains (Quizno's, Nathan's, Sbarro's, Burger King, etc), but none appealed.  I've had PE in the past, mostly at other airports, and knew it was a solid choice to fill me up without making me have to visit the plane's restroom over and over.

I asked for a sample of both breaded shrimp dishes they were featuring - Golden Treasure Shrimp (sweet-spicy with red and green pepper chunks) and Honey Walnut Srimp (creamy sweet sauce with candied walnuts).  I couldn't decide between the two, so I got both + veggie Chow Mein noodles ($9, $7 + $1 each upcharge for the shrimp).  I really liked both.  The breading was still slightly crispy, whole container was warm, and the shrimp was plentiful.

Ample seating in the open area in the middle of the food court.

text: Stayed overnight at the Hyatt Regency Airport and needed to get a quick meal to catch the SAG Awards airing that night. Decided to take away food and since I haven't gone to Panda Express since forever and there was barely a line, I went for it. Of course I had to get the Orange Chicken with fried rice and got a serving of the Shanghai Angus Steak as well just in case the Orange Chicken fails me.  Boy was I right getting another viand in handy as the Orange Chicken was too soggy and lacked flavor. Even the fried rice was shy of soy sauce! Good thing the Shanghai Angus Steak was impressively good! Seasoned well with the right mix of soy sauce and pepper.  Bottomline, if you want a quick and filling meal, this is OK but don't expect much!

text:
This location is in the food court of the Orlando international airport.  It was close to dinner time on a high traffic day during the holidays.

I witnessed about 5 employees in the kitchen area running around etc. and I waited in a decently long line patiently.  I reach the ordering spot, and asked for fried rice.  I was told they were out of fried rice for about 8 minutes... I looked at the line behind me and decided white rice would do me just fine!  But guess what? They were out of white rice too!! Even brown rice was out!

I know it was a higher traffic day being during the holiday season, but I was still disappointed in their lack of rice of any kind.

The beef with broccoli on top of my lo mein(!) was fine, but the string beans with chicken just tasted like it was made with Coca Cola... not really my flavor of choice.
